    <header class="article-header">
      <p class="article-meta">Published April 11, 2026 · By James Kim</p>
      <h1>INTJ vs INFJ: Differences, Similarities, and Compatibility</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">INTJ and INFJ are two of the rarest personality types in the Myers-Briggs framework, together making up roughly 4 to 5 percent of the general population. They share a dominant cognitive function — Introverted Intuition (Ni) — which gives both types an uncanny ability to see patterns, anticipate future outcomes, and think in abstractions that other types find difficult to follow. From the outside, INTJs and INFJs can look remarkably similar: quiet, intense, intellectual, and private. But beneath that surface, the way they process decisions, relate to other people, handle conflict, and choose careers diverges sharply. The difference comes down to a single letter — T versus F — but that letter represents a fundamentally different approach to the world. This guide breaks down every meaningful distinction, explores where the two types overlap, and examines how they interact in friendships, romantic relationships, and the workplace.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>Cognitive Function Stacks: The Foundation of the Difference</h2>
    <p>To truly understand INTJ versus INFJ, you need to look beyond the four-letter codes and examine the cognitive functions — the mental processes each type uses to take in information and make decisions. The function stack is ordered from most conscious and preferred (dominant) to least developed (inferior).</p>

    <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin:1.5rem 0">
      <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;background:var(--color-surface);font-size:0.95rem">
        <thead>
