            <th style="padding:0.75rem;text-align:left">INTJ Function</th>
            <th style="padding:0.75rem;text-align:left">INFJ Function</th>
            <th style="padding:0.75rem;text-align:left">What It Does</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
            <td style="padding:0.75rem"><strong>Dominant</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Ni — Introverted Intuition</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Ni — Introverted Intuition</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Pattern recognition, future vision, convergent insight</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
            <td style="padding:0.75rem"><strong>Auxiliary</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Te — Extraverted Thinking</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Fe — Extraverted Feeling</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">INTJ: organizes externally by logic and efficiency. INFJ: organizes externally by group harmony and values</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
            <td style="padding:0.75rem"><strong>Tertiary</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Fi — Introverted Feeling</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Ti — Introverted Thinking</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">INTJ: internal value system, personal ethics. INFJ: internal logical framework, analytical depth</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border)">
            <td style="padding:0.75rem"><strong>Inferior</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Se — Extraverted Sensing</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Se — Extraverted Sensing</td>
            <td style="padding:0.75rem">Awareness of physical environment, present-moment experience</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The shared dominant function, Introverted Intuition (Ni), is why these two types are so often confused with each other. Ni is focused, convergent, and future-oriented. Both INTJs and INFJs have an instinct for "knowing" something without being able to fully explain how they arrived at that conclusion. They synthesize patterns across time, context, and experience into a single unified insight. This is what makes both types strategic, visionary, and sometimes eerily prescient.</p>
    <p>The divergence happens at the auxiliary level. The INTJ's second function is Extraverted Thinking (Te), which drives them to organize the external world through systems, structures, efficiency, and measurable results. The INFJ's second function is Extraverted Feeling (Fe), which drives them to organize the external world through social harmony, emotional attunement, and interpersonal connection. This single difference — Te versus Fe — cascades into nearly every observable behavior.</p>

    <h2>Decision-Making: Thinking vs Feeling</h2>
    <p>This is where the INTJ and INFJ part ways most dramatically. When facing a decision, the INTJ asks: "What is the most logical, efficient, and effective course of action?" The INFJ asks: "How will this decision affect the people involved, and does it align with my values?"</p>
    <p><strong>INTJ decision-making characteristics:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Prioritizes objective criteria — data, evidence, outcomes</li>
      <li>Comfortable making unpopular decisions if they are logically correct</li>
      <li>Views emotional considerations as secondary to effectiveness</li>
      <li>Decides quickly once the analysis is complete — does not revisit unless new data emerges</li>
      <li>Can appear cold or dismissive of feelings, though this is rarely intentional</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>INFJ decision-making characteristics:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Weighs the emotional and relational impact heavily</li>
      <li>Seeks consensus and tries to find solutions that serve everyone</li>
      <li>May delay decisions to avoid hurting someone</li>
      <li>Uses an internal logical framework (Ti) as a check, but feelings guide the direction</li>
      <li>Can appear indecisive to Thinking types, though internally the INFJ is processing deeply</li>
    </ul>
    <p>A practical example: A manager must lay off one person from a team of five. The INTJ manager reviews each person's performance data, identifies the least productive team member, and makes the decision with minimal anguish — it is the logical choice. The INFJ manager considers each person's family situation, tenure, potential, and how the remaining team will feel about the decision. Both may arrive at the same conclusion, but the INFJ's process involves significantly more emotional weight and takes longer.</p>

    <h2>Communication Styles</h2>
    <p>Both INTJs and INFJs are introverts who prefer depth over breadth in conversation. Neither type enjoys small talk, and both tend to think carefully before speaking. But the <em>tone</em> and <em>focus</em> of their communication differ.</p>
    <p><strong>INTJ communication:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Direct and to the point — values precision over politeness</li>
      <li>Focuses on ideas, strategies, and problem-solving</li>
      <li>Delivers feedback bluntly, sometimes without softening language</li>
      <li>May forget (or choose not) to acknowledge emotions in a conversation</li>
      <li>Prefers written communication where they can structure their thoughts</li>
      <li>Dislikes repeating themselves or over-explaining</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>INFJ communication:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Diplomatic and considerate — cushions difficult messages with empathy</li>
      <li>Focuses on meaning, values, and the human dimension of any topic</li>
      <li>Gives feedback gently, framing criticism in terms of growth and potential</li>
      <li>Reads emotional undercurrents in conversation instinctively</li>
      <li>Prefers one-on-one conversations over group settings</li>
      <li>Dislikes confrontation and may avoid saying hard truths to preserve harmony</li>
    </ul>
    <p>In a conversation between the two types, the INTJ might say, "Your proposal has three flaws — here they are." The INFJ might say, "I appreciate the effort you put into this. I had a few thoughts on areas where we could strengthen it." Both are providing the same feedback, but the delivery could not be more different. INTJs sometimes find the INFJ's indirectness frustrating ("just say what you mean"), while INFJs may find the INTJ's bluntness hurtful ("you could have said that more kindly").</p>

    <h2>Career Preferences</h2>
    <p>Both types are drawn to careers that require strategic thinking, depth of knowledge, and meaningful impact. However, their career interests diverge based on whether they gravitate toward systems and efficiency (INTJ) or people and purpose (INFJ).</p>

    <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin:1.5rem 0">
      <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;background:var(--color-surface);font-size:0.95rem">
